arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase XI: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Main collapse level covering the whole trench
18.3 m north south -by- 12.5 m east west.

Locus 3 is a wash and collapse layer which covers the whole trench. This locus was filled with architectural fragments and has a high plaster content. It is differentiated by the overlying locus 1 by the slightly larger soil size, the presence of more plaster and inclusions and the soil color which has a Munsell color of 10yr 3/2, very dark grayish brown. The texture of the soil in locus 3 is course and the size of the grains is silt. Inclusions in this locus are mostly small plaster pieces, all sizes of stones, a medium amount of small and medium pottery and a small amount of small shells. The soil does ball and is consistent. The locus is in even condition. Most of the material in this locus appears to have been deposited by wash, but some may be uneven, late collapse so it is a sedimentation and collapse layer.
